                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><p><term>monument</term> <ref target="https://archwilio.org.uk/her/chi3/arch.php?lang=eng">Dyfed Archaeological Trust Historic Environment Record</ref>: <idno type="HER">3943</idno> St Gwinio's Church</p>
                                    <material type="stone">Gabbro</material> <note>Described as <q>dark grey gabbro, 20 per cent feldspar phenocrysts, 5 per cent of which are weathered, much chlorite. Weathered surface is light brown (7.5YR 6/2 - 6/4).</q> (Edwards 2007, 264).</note>
                                    <objectType key="monument">Pillar</objectType> 
                                    <dimensions unit='m'>
                                        <height>1.14</height>
                                        <width>0.38</width>
                                        <depth>0.305</depth>
                                        </dimensions></support> 

                                <condition/>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="vertical" rend="arris_up-up">The two incomplete ogham inscriptions are along <q>the original right (A/B) and left (A/D) angles of the face, both reading upwards from the original base</q>. <q>The ogham inscriptions are positioned so that the corresponding words are near their roman equivalents... The short central stroke of the second V on the left side suggests that the ogham inscription was cut after and shortened so as to avoid line 3 of the roman inscription</q> The roman-letter, Latin inscription consists of <q>three lines reading vertically downwards (from the original top of the monument)</q> (Edwards 2007, 264-267).</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The two ogham inscriptions are <rs type="execution" key="pocked" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/11.html">pocked</rs> or as Edwards describes <q>deeply incised, using broad strokes</q> (2007, 265). According to Edwards (2007, 264), the roman-letter inscription is <q>incised, using very broad lines</q> or as Macalister (1945, 359) noted <q>pocked and rubbed smooth</q>. The Latin inscription consists of capitals. The <q>letters in line 3 are smaller than the rest, owing to a lack of space. Three of the I's have triangular serifs. In line 1 VA are ligatured and the stroke of the V joins the A at the level of the crossbar; the second I is horizontal. In line 2 the A and V are rather rounded and the V is placed diagonally; the second B has separate loops. The V in line 3 is flattened and slightly rounded</q> (Edwards 2007, 264-265).
                                <height></height>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
