            <div type="translation">
                <div type="textpart" n="1">
                    <p><title>Ogham</title>: 'Bivv... grandson (or descendant) of Boddi...'</p>
                </div>
               </div>
              <div type="textpart" n="2"> <!--not displaying!-->
                  <p><title>Latin</title>: 'Of <foreign xml:lang="pgl">Bivadus</foreign> grandson (or descendant) of <foreign xml:lang="pgl">Bodibeve</foreign>'</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary"> <!--Needs rewriting and some points moved to apparatus-->
                        <p>The ogham inscription is a variant of the 'X son of Y' formula. Enough survives <q>...to demonstrate that the ogham inscriptions are broadly the same as the roman, but the forms of the names are slightly different and <foreign xml:lang="pgl">avi</foreign> is spelt <foreign xml:lang="pgl">avvi</foreign>... The names are both Irish. ...Both Llanwinio names contain the popular Insular Celtic name-element 'living' (Old Irish <foreign xml:lang="sga" corresp="https://dil.ie/5671">béo</foreign>, Welsh <foreign xml:lang="cy">byw</foreign>). ...Probably, however, it is a preform of the attested Old Irish masculine o-stem name <persName>Búaidbéo</persName>, in which case -E represents the Irish or Latin genitive -I... Linguistically it is not possible to choose between -BEV- and -BIV- wherever the readings are unclear, since both are possible...</q> (Edwards 2007, 264-267).</p>
                        <p><q>The roman-letter inscription uses the same variant of the 'X son of Y' formula in the genitive case with <foreign xml:lang="pgl">avi</foreign> rather than <foreign xml:lang="la">fili</foreign>... <foreign xml:lang="pgl">Avi</foreign>, meaning 'grandson' or 'descendant', is a straight transliteration of the primitive Irish found in the ogham <hi rend="italic">avvi</hi>, rather than a Latin translation (Edwards 2007, 264-267; Jackson 1953, 180-181)</q>.</p>
                    </div>
